Take one cluster and BLAST it manually against your database
Step 1 — Grab a single sequence

You already have this file:

53_Fresh/clusters/cluster_representatives.fasta

Extract just the first sequence:

head -n 2 cluster_representatives.fasta > test_sequence.fasta

Now check it:

cat test_sequence.fasta 
You should see something like:

>readID
ATGCGATCGATCGATC...
Step 2 — BLAST it manually

Run BLAST directly against your database:

blastn \
-query test_sequence.fasta \
-db ~/Downloads/Decona-Website-main/Decona_BLAST_DB/16SDB/16SDB_main/16SDB \
-outfmt "6 qseqid sseqid pident length evalue bitscore stitle"
🧪 Step 3 — Interpret the output

Example output might look like:

read1   JN133642.1   99.2   350   0.0   600   Dreissena polymorpha 16S ribosomal RNA

That means:

query sequence → matched Dreissena polymorpha

So:

✅ sequence valid
✅ BLAST database works
✅ taxonomy readable

If BLAST returns nothing

Possible causes:

1️⃣ sequence too short
2️⃣ poor quality read
3️⃣ prey not in database

But the pipeline itself would still be fine.

⚡ Step 4 — Faster trick (even simpler)

You can BLAST directly from the cluster file without extracting:
blastn \
-query cluster_representatives.fasta \
-db ~/Downloads/Decona-Website-main/Decona_BLAST_DB/16SDB/16SDB_main/16SDB \
-max_target_seqs 5 \
-outfmt "6 qseqid sseqid pident stitle"

